)ve, or Clive, from Old English <i>clif</i> ‘slope, bank, cliff’, or a topographic name from the same word. The Old English word was used not only in the sense of modern English <i>cliff</i> but also of much gentler slopes and frequently also of a riverbank or seashore."],"variants":[{"name":"Cleave","meanings":["English (Devon and Cornwall): variant of   Cliff  ."]},{"name":"Cliffe","meanings":["English: variant, common in Ireland, of   Cliff  ."]},{"name":"Cleve","meanings":["English: variant of   Cliff  .","German: variant of   Kleve  ."]},{"name":"Clifton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the very numerous places called Clifton, from Old English <i>clif</i> ‘slope’ (see   Cliff  ) + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."]},{"name":"Clift","meanings":["English: variant of   Cliff  ."]},{"name":"Clive","meanings":["English (Warwickshire): variant of   Cliff  . The name is also found in Wigtownshire, Scotland."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":7,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe ca